You can use [`java.lang.Runtime.exec`][1] to run simple code. This gives you back a `Process` and you can read its standard output directly without having to temporarily store the output on disk.

For example, here&#39;s a complete program that will showcase how to do it:

    import java.io.BufferedReader;
    import java.io.InputStreamReader;
    
    public class testprog {
        public static void main(String args[]) {
            String s;
            Process p;
            try {
                p = Runtime.getRuntime().exec(&quot;ls -aF&quot;);
                BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(
                    new InputStreamReader(p.getInputStream()));
                while ((s = br.readLine()) != null)
                    System.out.println(&quot;line: &quot; + s);
                p.waitFor();
                System.out.println (&quot;exit: &quot; + p.exitValue());
                p.destroy();
            } catch (Exception e) {}
        }
    }

