I saw the need to use defer to subscribe in another thread, in this case in a Scheduler provided by project reactor and programmed by Simon Basle.

 * [source using Mono.defer](https://github.com/rucko24/poc-sync-asyn/blob/main/src/main/java/com/simulation/syncvsasync/views/helloworld/SyncVsAsync.java#L97)

If you do a combination of `defer` plus `subscribeOn` and a `Schedulers.boundedElastic` you will make your code non-blocking or rather it will not **block** your application, removing contention in Reactor&#39;s default Scheduler at that time, perhaps Schedulers.parallel

----

The following image shows that the third component of a Combo, internally uses a defer plus a Scheduler, so as not to block the application.

![](https://rubn0x52.com/assets/img/reactiveFrecuencyMono.gif)


- ignore the method called `ui.access()` it is part of the vaadin framework.

```java
